&quot;I have a constructive suggestion - Get your panties unwadded and let the blood flow to your genitals again&quot;<br>
<br>
Ok, this kind of stuff just weakens your position.  This is, in debating, a fallacy by which you attempt to distract the reader from the issue at hand by irrelevant accusations against the your opponent.  How does this possibly strengthen your argument? The only way it can is if your opponent actually falls for it and feels the need to defend against it.  A smart debater will simply ignore it and move on, as it says nothing at all about the argument at hand and only serves to convince people that you cannot defend your point rationally and so must resort to unfounded personal attacks.<br>
<br>
