<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The only thing of mine you possibly control is my dick between your lips, bukake bucket. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So, how much was the tuition at the Ammelen School of Debate? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
And then this,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  It's apparent that an anti-ebay stance would hurt your profit margin, therefore you are trying to get people to ease up on their ebay hate. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
I take it you took my Playerauction comments at face value /boggle  What does that show about your mental faculties when you cannot detect sarcasm. I have already stated elsewhere in a post I'm sure you glossed over for convenience sake, that I would not personally find satisfaction in ebaying a toon as my main character. <br>
<br>
However, I did go on to point out the hate-filled extreme that the anti-ebayers go to in making their beliefs known is what has me really concerned. <br>
<br>
Moreover, my problem with anti-ebayers, while having nothing to do with your allegations that I'm some how engaged as a profiteer in the trafficking of characters, stems from two places:  <br>
<br>
1) THE HYPOCRACY CARD - Anti-ebayers will in the same breath say that it is okay to share accounts and even multiplay that second account on raids whilst turning around and lambasting a guild who has a ebayed cleric or monk who then are seen as somehow representing a &quot;taint&quot; on the accomplishments of that guild. We are to believe that one practice so changes the pristine gaming environment that Ammelen speaks of so as to allow us to say that &quot;ebaying is bad&quot; whilst &quot;account sharing is good.&quot; <br>
<br>
I say bullshit. If your &quot;pristine gaming environment&quot; is so damn important, let's crack down on everything and anything that upsets the cart. If that friend of yours with the cleric who gave you the account information is unable or in Lushe's words, &quot;not committed&quot; enough to his character to logon that night....then you LOSE the services of that toon. period....don't let someone else log the character on and then turn around and hypocritically lambast the guild who has a ebay monk and cleric saddled up. <br>
<br>
I can be every bit as tight assed as you Herder. <br>
<br>
2) The GREED CARD - It's postulated that ebay creates RL greed on the part of EQ players. This is a farce and they know it. I would imagine that the thoughts running through a rogue's mind after a Tunare kill, in Herder's Ebay-free wetdream world,  where a dagger dropped would be laced with some thought of &quot;man, I hope I get that item.&quot; Do we term that greed Herder?  Or how it is different? <br>
<br>
I've been along on Vulak kills where immediately after the killshot the people who haven't come up 7's on the loot award immediately start bitching and moaning about how this favorite or that favorite is likely to get the drop. Is this GREED? Is it put there, so to speak, by EBAY? <br>
<br>
You simply cannot, with a straight face tell me that GREED in EQ comes from the presence of items bought and sold for RL cash. <br>
<br>
GREED is a creation of human beings and the result of a GAME DESIGN where character advancement creates a sensation of &quot;need&quot; or &quot;greed&quot; for items. If ebay and RL bought and sold items disappear tomorrow, the next day's raids will STILL be filled with GREEDY people. Only the most extreme fool would deny that. <br>
<br>
So there you have it. Two sisters of the anti-ebay movement.....HYPOCRACY and GAME DESIGN INDUCED GREED combine to fashion something I think Vazaelle can do without -- that is, profound, deep-seated, pathological, unhealthy, HATE. <br>
<br>
Why do I, Truthreason, care about this? What personal interest do I have. <br>
<br>
I'll tell you why.....I despise extreme hate wherever I encounter it. And that it surfaces in a virtual world makes it even more of a concern. If you think that hating is the way of the world, you'll never see or care to understand my point of view. However, if you are inclined to want something better than hate, you might be inclined to give what I said a chance. <br>
<br>
